<subsection xml:id="aligned-summary">
<title>Student Perspective</title>
<p>
Day four began by noting three things.
<ol>
<li><p>Most students were able to successfully create and upload an
example LaTeX document to GitHub from day three.</p></li>
<li><p>The first LaTeX writing assignment will be uploaded for students
to begin working on by the end of the day. Its instructions will be self
contained and require about one page of work by students.</p></li>
<li><p>Each student will be required to type and submit a summary of one
of the lectures for this course. Students will volunteer for a lecture
that has not already been summarized by another student, beginning with
the day three lecture. More details can be found in the
<c>math2753_summaries.220.pdf</c> file on the new, class Google Drive
link.</p></li>
</ol>

The day continued by briefly reviewing topics from day three and
introducing new LaTeX features and concepts. The three most important
were the <c>align</c>, <c>itemize</c>, and <c>enumerate</c>
environments.
</p>

<p>
<ol>
	<li><p> Create a table of contents (TOC) with the
<c>\tableofcontents</c> command.</p></li>
	<li><p> Create sections and subsections with the <c>\section{}</c>
and <c>\subsubsection{}</c> commands.</p></li>
	<ol>
		<li><p> A <c>sub</c> prefix may be added multiple times to
create many levels of nested subsections.</p></li>
		<li><p> The code must be recompiled twice to appear in the
TOC.</p></li>
	</ol>
	<li><p> Two dollar signs <c>$ ... $</c> may be used in place of the
<c>\( ... \)</c> command and two double-dollar signs <c>$$ ... $$</c>
may be used in place of the <c>\[ ... \]</c> command. However, the
instructor does not prefer it. <em> More importantly, the developers
recommend against it!</em></p></li>
	<li><p> During compiling errors, individual lines or blocks of code
may be commented out to help pinpoint and troubleshoot the
errors.</p></li>
	<li><p> To render a left-apostrophe or quotation mark, the
apostrophe character that is usually found one the same key as the tilde
symbol must be used.</p></li>
	<li><p> To render characters that already have assigned usage in the
<latex /> typesetting language, the characters must be prefixed with a
backward slash. For example, to display the ampersand character we would
type <c>\&amp;</c>.</p></li>
</ol>
</p>
</subsection>

</section>

